Find the limit:

{eq}\lim \limits_{(x,y) \to (2,2)} \frac {2x^2y-8xy+8y}  {(x-2)^2+y^2}

{/eq}
{eq}\lim \limits_{(x,y) \to (2,2)} \frac {2x^2y-8xy+8y}  {(x-2)^2+y^2}

{/eq}

Rearrange terms:

{eq}=\lim \limits_{(x,y) \to (2,2)} \frac {2y(x^2-4x+4)}  {(x-2)^2+y^2}

{/eq}

Factor the numerator:

{eq}=\lim \limits_{(x,y) \to (2,2)} \frac {2y(x-2)^2}  {(x-2)^2+y^2}

{/eq}

Cancel out terms:

{eq}=\lim \limits_{(x,y) \to (2,2)} \frac {2y}  {1+\frac{y^2}{(x-2)^2}}

{/eq}

Plug in (2,2):

{eq}=\frac {2(2)}  {1+\frac{2^2}{(2-2)^2}}

{/eq}

{eq}=\frac {4}  {1+\infty}

{/eq}

{eq}=0

{/eq}

Multiply the following two matrices:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
2 & -1 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\]
and
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cccc}
-1 & -1 & 0 & 0 \\
-2 & -3 & -1 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\]
The multiplication of these two matrices results in:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
2(-1) + (-1)(-2) & 2(-1) + (-1)(-3) \\
\end{array}
\right)
\]
Simplifying the elements gives us:
\[
\left(
\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & -1 & 1 & -3 \\
\end{array}
\right)
\]

